UNITED NATIONS — Ratko Mladic, the former Bosnian Serb general charged with orchestrating the largest mass killing of civilians in Europe since World War II, was arrested Thursday in Serbia, ending a nearly 16-year manhunt that stood as a test of the West’s commitment to holding accused war criminals accountable.
Mladic, 69, is accused of commanding troops responsible for the deaths of thousands of civilians during a 46-month siege of Sarajevo, the Bosnian capital, and for slaughtering nearly 8,000 Bosnian Muslims, mostly men and boys, near the town of Srebrenica in July 1995. Mladic’s capture provided some small vindication to Western powers, which had pressed for his arrest in recent years despite their record of standing aside as Bosnian Serb forces killed more than 200,000 people.
